news_raw.title: Heard on the Street Friday Recap: Confidence Dips
news_raw.summary: Consumer confidence was unexpectedly weak, adding to the spate of data pointing to a sluggish economy.  A preliminary University of Michigan index reading for September came in at 55.4, a decline from August and below the 58.1 economists anticipated.  Eyes now turn to the Federal Reserve, which is expected on Wednesday to cut interest rates to try to restimulate growth.

news_raw.title: Bill Ackman’s Main Fund Is Up 25% in 2025. These 2 Investments Are Helping.
news_raw.summary: Bill Ackman is having an impressive year: His main investment vehicle has returned 25% and been helped by its sizable holdings in  Freddie Mac  and Fannie Mae, whose shares have more than quadrupled in 2025.  The fund’s U.S.-listed shares closed 1% higher on Friday at $63.41 apiece after hitting a record high of $63.70 earlier in the session.  The shares have returned 32% so far this year, topping the NAV performance as the discount to NAV has narrowed.

news_raw.title: Dow Jones Futures: Nvidia, Meta, Tesla In Focus; Markets Want This From Fed Meeting
news_raw.summary: Dow Jones futures edged higher Sunday night, along with S&P 500 futures and Nasdaq futures. The Federal Reserve meeting headlines the coming week. The stock market rally powered to record highs this past week.

news_raw.title: Stocks hesitant in Asia, with a lot riding on Fed decision
news_raw.summary: Global shares traded steadily near record highs on Monday ahead of an action-packed week that looks certain to see the U.S. Federal Reserve resume its easing cycle, and perhaps leave the door wide open to a series of cuts.  The Bank of Canada is also expected to cut rates by a quarter point this week, while the Bank of Japan and the Bank of England are both expected to hold rates steady.  MSCI's all-country index hovered just shy of last week's record highs, while stocks in Europe rose 0.3% and S&P 500 futures and Nasdaq futures were both steady.

news_raw.title: Fed Meeting; FedEx, Lennar, Bullish Earnings; and More to Watch This Week
news_raw.summary: The Fed will take center stage this week, with an interest-rate cut all but assured to be announced on Wednesday.

news_raw.title: Options Traders Craving Volatility Look Past Fed to Jobs Data
news_raw.summary: The Fed is expected to cut interest rates on Wednesday and quarterly equity options on stocks, exchange-traded funds and indexes will expire Friday in an event that some say clears out dealer positions.  While those ordinarily look quite enticing for traders betting on bigger market swings, this time they aren’t expecting volatility to make an immediate return.  With a 25 basis-point rate cut fully priced in, investors will be watching the press conference closely for dovish or hawkish rhetoric from Fed Chair Jerome Powell.
